      <p>The phrase "as is, where is" shows up in some Queensland property contracts, particularly in deceased estate sales, distressed sales, and situations where the seller has limited knowledge of the property's condition. It signals to buyers that the seller is not making representations about the property's state and does not intend to remedy defects before settlement. What it does not do is remove the seller's legal disclosure obligations under Queensland law.</p>

      <p>This distinction matters. Many sellers, and occasionally even agents, assume that including this clause in a contract removes the need to disclose known defects or material facts. It does not. If anything, misunderstanding this point is one of the more reliable ways to find yourself in a post-settlement dispute.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the clause actually means in a Queensland contract</h2>
      <p>In a Queensland residential property contract, "as is, where is" is a shorthand for a few things operating together. It typically means the buyer accepts the property in its current physical condition at the time of contract, the seller is not warranting that structures are compliant or in working order, and the seller is not committing to repair or remediate defects identified in a building inspection. It is, in essence, a way of saying: what you see is what you get, and I am not fixing anything before we settle.</p>

      <p>The clause is often used alongside a reduced purchase price. A buyer who agrees to an as-is sale accepts more risk in exchange for a price that reflects that risk. In theory, this is a straightforward commercial arrangement. In practice, it only holds if the seller has been genuinely transparent about known issues.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What it does not remove: your disclosure obligations</h2>
      <p>Queensland property law requires sellers to disclose certain things about a property regardless of any as-is clause. The seller's disclosure statement attached to the contract must accurately reflect what the seller knows about the property. Known defects that would be considered material to a buyer's decision to purchase must be disclosed. Unapproved structures, known encumbrances, flood history, contamination, and neighbourhood disputes that the seller is aware of are all examples of information that cannot simply be omitted because the contract says as-is.</p>

      <p>The Property Law Act and the Body Corporate and Community Management Act in Queensland both impose disclosure obligations that sit above what any individual contract clause can override. An as-is contract clause deals with physical condition and repair obligations. It does not deal with misrepresentation or the seller's duty to not actively conceal known defects.</p>

      <p>If a seller uses an as-is clause to avoid disclosing a material defect they knew about, and that defect is discovered by the buyer after settlement, the buyer may have grounds to pursue damages or, in serious cases, to seek rescission. The as-is clause will not be a reliable defence in that situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the clause legitimately protects sellers</h2>
      <p>There are circumstances where an as-is clause is both appropriate and commercially sensible. Deceased estate sales are the most common example. An executor or administrator selling a property on behalf of an estate often has limited personal knowledge of the property's maintenance history, what repairs were done and when, or the condition of systems like plumbing and electrical. They are not the people who lived there, and they cannot reasonably warrant things they do not know. An as-is clause in a deceased estate context is transparent and appropriate: it tells buyers upfront that the estate is not in a position to make representations and that buyers should conduct their own due diligence.</p>

      <p>Distressed sales, mortgagee sales, and situations where a property has been tenanted for many years and the owner has not had regular access are other contexts where the clause appears legitimately. In each case, the logic is the same: the seller is being honest about the limits of their knowledge, not attempting to hide something specific.</p>

      <p>The clause also provides protection for sellers who have previously disclosed known issues in the contract documents. If a seller discloses that the deck is unapproved, the hot water system is at end of life, and the pool pump is not functioning, and then the contract includes an as-is clause confirming the buyer accepts those conditions, that is a legitimate use. The disclosure is still there; the clause simply confirms the buyer is not expecting remediation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How buyers interpret it and the impact on offers</h2>
      <p>Experienced buyers and their conveyancers recognise an as-is clause immediately. Their response is generally one of two things. Some buyers, particularly investors and developers who are comfortable with risk and have the resources to manage issues, will proceed with appropriate due diligence and price in what they find. These buyers are unlikely to be deterred by the clause itself.</p>

      <p>Other buyers, particularly owner-occupiers purchasing their family home, will view the clause with significant caution. For this group, an as-is sale often triggers either a more aggressive building inspection process, a substantially lower offer to account for unknown risk, or a decision not to proceed at all. If your target market is owner-occupiers, an as-is approach may reduce your buyer pool and your outcome compared to addressing known issues directly and presenting a property with full disclosure.</p>

      <p>The impact on sale price depends heavily on the property, the market, and how the clause is presented. A well-located property in strong demand may absorb the clause with minimal price impact. A property where the clause is the only signal buyers receive about its condition will typically see significant discounting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Risks for sellers who misuse the clause</h2>
      <p>The practical risk for sellers who include an as-is clause without proper disclosure is that it may not actually protect them. Courts and tribunals in Queensland have consistently taken the view that a contractual clause does not override a seller's duty not to engage in misleading or deceptive conduct. If a building inspection report from a previous sale campaign revealed a serious structural defect, and the seller subsequently listed the property as-is without disclosing that report or that defect, the as-is clause is unlikely to insulate the seller from a post-settlement claim.</p>

      <p>Before using an as-is clause, get advice from your conveyancer about what you are actually required to disclose. The time to work through this is before the contract is signed, not after a buyer discovers something that was known and not disclosed.</p>

